[2] USA (Wisconsin)
Date: Fri 17 Oct 2014
Source: The Herald-Independent [edited]
http://www.hngnews.com/monona_cottage_grove/article_f2afba82-546d-11e4-abff-0017a43b2370.html


Public Health Madison and Dane County [PHMDC, Wisconsin] has been notified of test results of 5 cases of a respiratory virus making its rounds across the area, but Monona Grove school officials say there is no reason for concern. Enterovirus D68 (EV-D68) is a virus that is reportedly causing mild to severe respiratory illness (runny nose, cough, difficulty breathing) with and without fever. Enteroviruses are very common. There are more than 100 types of enterovirus, although this EV-D68 strain has previously been uncommon in the United States, according to the PHMDC.

In other states, presumed EV-D68 outbreaks are resulting in growing numbers of children requiring emergency room visits and hospitalizations, primarily for difficulties with breathing and severe asthma. No such details are currently available regarding the Dane County cases.

Guidelines for students who are ill are posted on the district website [and] are occasionally put into school newsletters for parents. These guidelines focus on fever, vomiting, diarrhea, severe nausea, infectious diseases, rashes and injuries. If a child has a fever of 100 degrees Fahrenheit [about 37.8 degrees Celsius] or more, the child should be kept home until 24 hours after the fever has resolved without giving fever-reducing medication. Vomiting, diarrhea and severe nausea are symptoms to keep the child home until he or she is able to tolerate a normal diet for 24 hours after the symptoms are resolved. Rashes or patches of broken, itchy skin need to be examined by a doctor if they appear to be spreading or not improving. Some rashes may need to be covered while the child is at school. EV-D68 can be found in saliva, nasal mucus or sputum and, like the common cold, likely spreads from person to person when an infected person coughs or sneezes, or a person touches contaminated surfaces. Infants, children and teenagers are more likely than adults to get infected with enteroviruses and become sick.

"It is common to see more respiratory illnesses at this time of year caused by many different viruses," said Amanda Kita-Yarbro, communicable disease epidemiologist for PHMDC. "Usually symptoms are mild and limited, but if you are concerned about your own or your child's symptoms, it's important to call your health care provider." EV-D68 is not a reportable disease, which means that hospitals and healthcare providers are not required to report cases to local health departments.

[byline: Kevin Passon]

